Here's how to implement all three requirements:

## 1. Custom "Cancel" Back Button (on EditProductPage.xaml)

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

## 2 & 3. Navigation Guard with Confirmation Dialog (in AppShell.xaml.cs)

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    // Only intercept back navigation from EditProductPage
    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();   // user chose "Stay" ‚Äî cancel navigation

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

## 3. ViewModel BackCommand (triggers the same guard)

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
private async Task Back()
{
    // This navigates back, which fires OnNavigating above
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**Key points:**

- `GetDeferral()` is required for async checks ‚Äî without it the navigation completes before your dialog returns.
- `args.Cancel()` stops the navigation if the user wants to stay.
- The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` fires your custom command, but because it calls `GoToAsync("..")`, the same `OnNavigating` guard still applies.
- Expose a `HasUnsavedChanges` property on your page (or check via the ViewModel) so the guard knows when to prompt.
